</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="4FE3E1498CCEE64ED0599149D5E836C0" pageId="502" pageNumber="503" type="reference_group">
<paragraph id="8B64969E88DC5760B80078F42418E34F" pageId="502" pageNumber="503">
<taxonomicName id="C64A7755018E9C1232F8FD123942C2FC" authorityName="Dejean" authorityYear="1828" class="Insecta" family="Carabidae" genus="Myas" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Coleoptera" pageId="502" pageNumber="503" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="cyanescens">Myas cyanescens</taxonomicName>
Dejean, 1828: 425. Type locality: 
<normalizedToken id="7B53EBD67426F573DE0694E71E31C43E" originalValue="«Amérique">&quot;Amerique</normalizedToken>
septentrionale&quot; (original citation), restricted to &quot;M[oun]t Toby [Franklin County], Mass[achusetts]&quot; by Lindroth (1966: 445). One syntype in MHNP (Lindroth 1955b: 14).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="9732119CB33F97446C976728F425DFEF" pageId="502" pageNumber="503">
<taxonomicName id="50E6DA58E86DCCFB16489345B2F9781B" class="Insecta" family="Carabidae" genus="Myas" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Coleoptera" pageId="502" pageNumber="503" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="foveatus">Myas foveatus</taxonomicName>
LeConte, 1847: 355. Type locality: &quot;NovEboraci [= New York]&quot; (original citation). Lectotype (♀), designated by Bousquet (1999: 91), in MCZ [# 5599]. Synonymy established by LeConte (1869b: 249), confirmed by Lindroth (1955b: 14).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="F9654D85A1E71C64CC8E93CA63474AAC" pageId="502" pageNumber="503">
<taxonomicName id="6CC464C540090F3D116CE433094E2264" authorityName="Allen" authorityYear="1980" class="Insecta" family="Carabidae" genus="Neomyas" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Coleoptera" pageId="502" pageNumber="503" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="lindrothi">Neomyas lindrothi</taxonomicName>
Allen, 1980: 20. Type locality: &quot;Graybeard Mountain, North Carolina&quot; (original citation). Holotype (♂) location unknown (missing in AMNH, Richard L. Hoffman pers. comm. 2003). 
<emphasis id="E7108477E889E108588BC5C3F08D4AE9" bold="true" pageId="502" pageNumber="503">New synonymy</emphasis>
. Note. Allen (1980) established 
<taxonomicName id="053AF400597F6FFC1E5FBBC2D1BD74B1" authorityName="Allen" authorityYear="1980" class="Insecta" family="Carabidae" genus="Neomyas" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Coleoptera" pageId="502" pageNumber="503" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="lindrothi">
<emphasis id="A4BCFED812A0919D19B3142E895CA437" italics="true" pageId="502" pageNumber="503">Neomyas lindrothi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
exclusively on the presence of a distinct scale group on the right lateral surface of the endophallus; this group of scales being absent in 
<taxonomicName id="060D457FF1D26263D8F7DA295DD5A2A1" authorityName="Dejean" authorityYear="1828" class="Insecta" family="Carabidae" genus="Myas" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Coleoptera" pageId="502" pageNumber="503" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="cyanescens">
<emphasis id="9FB1A4B7F3678B704789FDA609B3EF90" italics="true" pageId="502" pageNumber="503">Myas cyanescens</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. In my opinion, this character alone is probably not of specific nature considering among others that the endophallic scales are extremely variable in members of 
<taxonomicName id="1A790AB317662ED4290D7C7847E3626B" authorityName="Dejean" authorityYear="1828" class="Insecta" family="Carabidae" genus="Myas" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Coleoptera" pageId="502" pageNumber="503" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="cyanescens">
<emphasis id="86D6FE49BD82F779EFA44C3724EFA39A" italics="true" pageId="502" pageNumber="503">Myas cyanescens</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
as noted by Allen (1980: 24) himself.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="CD00DDC545A5F690A97CB5A86D1E7B5D" pageId="502" pageNumber="503" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="6165C386FA4A46D79F9FAF278B48C0E5" pageId="502" pageNumber="503">Distribution.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="9FF0B9EFEF5377281BFFB5E19917FA76" pageId="502" pageNumber="503">
This species is found from &quot;Nova Scotia&quot; (Larochelle and 
<normalizedToken id="4C62728EA31D74AD024DB4AAA0394849" originalValue="Larivière">Lariviere</normalizedToken>
1990a: 29) to northwestern Minnesota (Allen 1980: 24), south to northern Alabama (
<normalizedToken id="91092F75C0067093AE19CB1D81B52032" originalValue="Löding">Loeding</normalizedToken>
1945: 15) and Georgia (Fattig 1949: 21, as 
<taxonomicName id="8CA7791256C7FEA3A99172D4ECB304F0" class="Insecta" family="Carabidae" genus="Myas" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Coleoptera" pageId="502" pageNumber="503" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="foveatus">
<emphasis id="BD5C22032A2BBFAB932856F52A5C82B7" italics="true" pageId="502" pageNumber="503">Myas foveatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
). A specimen simply labeled from Texas is known (Allen 1980: 26).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
